<subSubSection pageId="38" pageNumber="39" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="38.[151,1436,685,1214]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,461,793,818]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" reason="1">Differential diagnosis.</emphasis>
The habitus (
<figureCitation box="[613,694,793,817]" captionStart="FIGURES 65–68" captionStartId="36.[151,263,1726,1749]" captionTargetBox="[219,1357,207,1691]" captionTargetId="figure-134@36.[211,1376,193,1705]" captionTargetPageId="36" captionText="FIGURES 65–68. Epimetopus, dorsal and lateral habitus, and perpendicular to pronotum, holotypes and lectotype of E. costatus." pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Fig. 68</figureCitation>
) is similar to that of several species in the 
<emphasis box="[1168,1266,793,817]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Costatus</emphasis>
group; reliable determinations will be based on examination of the male genitalia. The aedeagus is somewhat similar in general to that of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Perkins" authorityYear="2012" box="[237,371,866,889]" class="Insecta" family="Epimetopidae" genus="Epimetopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="angustus">
<emphasis box="[237,371,866,889]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">E. angustus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[390,487,865,889]" captionStart="FIGURES 28–31" captionStartId="22.[151,264,1569,1592]" captionTargetBox="[173,1417,261,1547]" captionTargetId="figure-174@22.[151,1436,237,1571]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURES 28–31. Epimetopus, aedeagi of holotypes." pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Figs. 28</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[503,535,865,889]" captionStart="FIGURES 69–72" captionStartId="37.[151,264,2007,2030]" captionTargetBox="[222,1365,677,1986]" captionTargetId="figure-145@37.[196,1390,658,2020]" captionTargetPageId="37" captionText="FIGURES 69–72. Epimetopus, aedeagi of holotypes, and lectotype of E. costatus." pageId="38" pageNumber="39">72</figureCitation>
); both have slender, slightly arching parameres. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="A. Oliva" authorityYear="1984" box="[1101,1253,865,889]" class="Insecta" family="Epimetopidae" genus="Epimetopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="burruyacu">
<emphasis box="[1101,1253,865,889]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">E. burruyacu</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Perkins" authorityYear="2012" class="Insecta" family="Epimetopidae" genus="Epimetopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="angustus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">E. angustus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in that the parameres are shorter compared with the length of the basal piece; also, the median lobe is wider and shorter. Externally, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="A. Oliva" authorityYear="1984" box="[488,635,937,961]" class="Insecta" family="Epimetopidae" genus="Epimetopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="burruyacu">
<emphasis box="[488,635,937,961]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">E. burruyacu</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is larger that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Perkins" authorityYear="2012" box="[788,918,938,961]" class="Insecta" family="Epimetopidae" genus="Epimetopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="angustus">
<emphasis box="[788,918,938,961]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">E. angustus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(ca. 1.55 vs. 
<quantity box="[1068,1172,937,961]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.31" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" unit="mm" value="1.31">1.31 mm</quantity>
), has the elytral carinae and pronotal sculpture slightly less developed, and has smaller elytral punctures (
<figureCitation box="[1061,1155,973,997]" captionStart="FIGURES 24–27" captionStartId="20.[151,264,1726,1749]" captionTargetBox="[219,1362,216,1696]" captionTargetId="figure-144@20.[204,1382,193,1705]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURES 24–27. Epimetopus holotypes, dorsal and lateral habitus, and perpendicular to pronotum." pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Figs. 24</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1166,1197,973,997]" captionStart="FIGURES 65–68" captionStartId="36.[151,263,1726,1749]" captionTargetBox="[219,1357,207,1691]" captionTargetId="figure-134@36.[211,1376,193,1705]" captionTargetPageId="36" captionText="FIGURES 65–68. Epimetopus, dorsal and lateral habitus, and perpendicular to pronotum, holotypes and lectotype of E. costatus." pageId="38" pageNumber="39">68</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="38" pageNumber="39" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="38.[151,1436,685,1214]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">
<emphasis box="[199,344,1009,1034]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,337,1009,1034]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Description</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
Size: 
<typeStatus box="[421,519,1009,1033]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">holotype</typeStatus>
(length/width, mm): body (length from anterior margin of pronotum to elytral apices) 1.55/0.78; head (width) 0.41; pronotum 0.55/0.56; elytra 1.00/0.78. Habitus and sculpture as illustrated (
<figureCitation box="[159,244,1081,1105]" captionStart="FIGURES 65–68" captionStartId="36.[151,263,1726,1749]" captionTargetBox="[219,1357,207,1691]" captionTargetId="figure-134@36.[211,1376,193,1705]" captionTargetPageId="36" captionText="FIGURES 65–68. Epimetopus, dorsal and lateral habitus, and perpendicular to pronotum, holotypes and lectotype of E. costatus." pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Fig. 68</figureCitation>
). Head piceous, dorsum red, venter and coxae dark brown, maxillary palpi testaceous. Eye with ca. 3–4 facets between canthus and posterior margin. Protibiae slightly arcuate. Elytral granules linking punctures. Metaventral depression moderately deep, ca. six granules along base.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1262,1189,1214]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="38.[151,1436,685,1214]" box="[199,1262,1189,1214]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,352,1189,1214]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" reason="1">Distribution.</emphasis>
Currently known from two narrowly separated localities in 
<collectingCountry box="[1025,1136,1189,1213]" name="Argentina" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Argentina</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[1151,1250,1189,1213]" captionStart="FIGURE 126" captionStartId="86.[151,250,1870,1893]" captionTargetBox="[283,1304,337,1849]" captionTargetId="figure-105@86.[283,1304,337,1849]" captionTargetPageId="86" captionText="FIGURE 126. Geographical distributions of Epimetopus species." pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Fig. 126</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
